Confirmation of brain death

#2017GM-OCT/Q7
A patient who has suffered brain death is legally and clinically dead.

  • Some spinal reflexes may be present in patients with brain death.

The three essential findings of confirmation of brain death are

  1. Coma
  2. Apnoea
    1. Absense of spontaneous breathing with CO2 > 60 or rise of > 20 from baseline after 8 to 10 minutes of aponoea. (need to do ABGs to check this)
  3. Absence of brain stem reflexes
    1. Loss of pupillary light reflex.
    2. Loss of occulocephalic reflex -
      1. Dolls eye reflex should normally be in tact.
      2. Movement of eyes to contralateral side with lateral head movement.
    3. Loss of corneal reflex
    4. Loss of occulovestibular reflex (Caloric test) - 50cc of ice water into the ear will cause eyes to move to the ipsilateral side.
    5. Loss of gag reflex
    6. Loss of cough reflex.

Ancillary tests:

  • Imaging (USS, Angiography) to confirm absence of cerebral blood flow.
  • Flat trace on EEG for > 30 minutes.

Gamma-glutamyl transpeptidase

(GGT, gamma GT, gamma glutamyl transferase)

Enzyme found in hepatocytes, liver epithelium and many other tissues in various systems (kidney, seminal vesicles etc). The highest concentration is in the kidney.
Newborn levels are x5 of adult levels.

Clinical utility:

  1. "confers liver specificity" to elevated transaminases.
  2. Can be used to identify alcohol abuse.
  3. Can be use to see if raised ALP is coming from the liver or the bone.
  4. Half life 14 days -> comes back to normal after alcohol abuse in about 4 -5 weeks.
  • Increased GGT is also seen in
    • phenytoin treatment
    • Liver disease (hepatitis, cirrhosis, cholestasis etc.)
    • Alcoholism
    • Carcinoma of breast, lung, prostate

Otherwise, no better than trasnaminases.

  • Painful and tender wasting of the quadriceps muscles seen in older men with DM.
  • CSF protein is elevated.
  • Also called lumbosacral radiculoplexus neuropathy (LRPN)
  • Pathophysiology : The most likely cause is ischemic injury from a nonsystemic microvasculitis.

Neuroleptic malignant syndrome

#2017GM-OCT/Q09
Pathogenesis:

  • can occur in background of Asthma / Cyctic fibrosis
    Suspect in patient with poorly controlled asthma despite increasing medications.
  • Mucus plugs -> lung collapse; can cause proximal bronchiectasis
  • Recurrent episodes -> upper lobe fibrosis
    Must be distinguished from the following:
ABPA Aspergilloma Invasive aspergillosis Aspergillus pneumonia
Patients with asthma or CF Occurs in immunocompromised patients Rare, Occurs with chronic low dose prednisilone
migratory or non resolving infiltrates on CXR / atelectasis due to mucous plug A fungall "ball"
Air screscent on CXR
Allergic reaction to aspergillus;
There is no tissue invasion
Dx: SKin prick test with aspergillus antigen
serology		 Serum galactomannan
Manage with prednisolone
IV itraconazole in resistant cases
 IV Amphotericin
Monitor with CXR, IgE levels and blood eosinophil levels

Investigations:
Aspergillus specific IgG and IgE

#2017GM-OCT/Q13

[!WARNING] Spinal muscular atrophy is the odd one out :
It's a neuropathy.

  • Type I: wednick hoffman - presents at birth. (60%)
    • Symptoms appear at birth or within 6 months with difficulty of swallowing on sucking
  • Type II is intermediate. (8 - 18 months)
  • Type III (after 18 months)
  • Type IV - rare variant (appears in 30s)

Progressive muscular atrophy is a type of motor neuron disease

[!TIP] Mnemonic: Duchenne's -> Disastrous / Death by 20
Duchenne is worse than Beckers

Becker muscular dystrophy Duchenne Muscular dystrophy Fascioscapulohumeral Myotonic dystrophy Spinal muscular atrophy
Progressive, symmetrical muscle weakness and atrophy with pseudohypertrophic calves may be seen.

Limb girdle muscular dystrophy

Can be difficult to differentiate from Becker muscular dystrophy.
#autosomal-Recessive

  • Impairment of consciousness is the cardinal feature.
  • Delirium is rapid in onset and fluctuating in course.
  • Thinking is slow and confused but rich in detail. Ideas of reference and delusions are common.
  • Mood: labile and anxious, irritable, depressed. etc
  • Perception: visual hallucinations / misinterpretations. Tactile and auditory hallucinations are less common.
  • 'False positives' can occur in empyema, mesothelioma, parapneumonic effusion, haemorrhagic effusion, rheumatoid pleurisy etc.

"Autoimmune hepatitis (AIH) is designated as type 1 or 2 (AIH-1/2) on the basis of serum autoantibody (Ab) profiles"
Source
However, these subtypes have not been established as distinct clinical or pathological entities.

  • Type I AIH has ANA and anti-smooth muscle antibodies.
  • Type II - anti liver kidney microsomal antibodies. LKM1

Biopsy is mandatory to confirm the diagnosis; It will show interface hepatitis and chronic active hepatitis.

  • Initial symptoms: obstructive jaundice, pruritus, fatigue etc.
  • Often complicated by recurrent cholangitis and cholangiocarcinoma. (20% will develop cholangiocarcinoma)
    • Also can cause osteoporosis
    • Fat soluble vitamin malabsorption
  • Type III: immune complex mediated.
    • Arthus reaction is a type of Type III reaction
    • The Arthus reaction involves the in situ formation of antigen antibody complexes.
    • Manifests as a local vasculitis (at the bite or injection site) due to deposition of of IgG based immune complexes in dermal tissue.

Bronchiectasis

#2017GM-OCT/Q10
Once patients develop bronchiectasis, most commonly isolated organisms are haemophillus and pseudomonas and streptococcus pneumoniae.

[!TIP] mnemonic:
Extra-articular complications all begin with A:

  • Apical fibrosis
  • Anterior uveitis
  • Aortic regurgitation
  • Achilles tendonitis
  • AV node block
  • Amyloidosis
